188
00:21:24,612 --> 00:21:37,343
But you must remember in those days they're very extended families and I can't imagine that he did it without long consultation and argument and all that sort of stuff and cajoling.

189
00:21:37,844 --> 00:21:44,589
And then finally I'm sure he said to them, as I said to my mother, I'm only doing it for three years.

190
00:21:44,569 --> 00:22:08,265
when i said that she disappeared with this cloud of absolute i said to her i'm going to join the order and she just collapsed into this awful weeping and i put my arm around and said mom i said i'm only going for three years and she stopped it was just it was just because yes because it you know she saw it as an abandonment

191
00:22:10,169 --> 00:22:15,117
So one presumes that he did have the goodwill of the family behind him.

192
00:22:15,659 --> 00:22:17,962
And there comes this point where he reaches a river.

193
00:22:18,104 --> 00:22:20,248
So here it is, you see, crossing the Rubicon.

194
00:22:20,728 --> 00:22:29,223
See, there's a point where we make that crossing, where we've built up the faith, we've built up the understanding, and finally we make that leap of faith, you see.

195
00:22:29,203 --> 00:22:33,628
Now, in terms of the Buddha, okay, it was a big dramatic moment.

196
00:22:33,689 --> 00:22:34,450
It's part of the myth.

197
00:22:34,809 --> 00:22:36,132
But for us, it's every day.

198
00:22:36,192 --> 00:22:38,673
Every day you have to make that leap of faith.

199
00:22:38,733 --> 00:22:42,057
Every day you've got to cross that ruby, can't you see?

200
00:22:42,077 --> 00:22:43,199
And it's crossing from what?

201
00:22:43,278 --> 00:22:47,943
It's crossing from the worldly life to the spiritual life.

202
00:22:47,963 --> 00:22:58,536
And he cuts off all his hair, which was the idea of those days, throws all his rich clothes away, dons rag robes,

203
00:22:58,516 --> 00:23:03,141
And even leaves his horse, Kantaka, who dies out of grief.

204
00:23:03,862 --> 00:23:04,041
See?

205
00:23:04,061 --> 00:23:05,544
It was terrible.

206
00:23:05,564 --> 00:23:06,525
But Channa can't leave him.

207
00:23:06,545 --> 00:23:09,087
I think he follows him in the end.

208
00:23:09,107 --> 00:23:09,448
Is that right?

209
00:23:09,647 --> 00:23:11,309
He follows him, doesn't he, Channa?

210
00:23:11,770 --> 00:23:12,531
Eventually.

211
00:23:12,551 --> 00:23:13,172
Later on, is it?

212
00:23:13,211 --> 00:23:13,653
No, that's right.

213
00:23:13,673 --> 00:23:14,733
So he goes off first.

214
00:23:15,955 --> 00:23:17,037
So there we have it, you see.

215
00:23:17,416 --> 00:23:21,721
So finally, you might say, he's cut from the world in life.

216
00:23:23,625 --> 00:23:27,871
So that's another point of contemplation for us.

217
00:23:27,911 --> 00:23:33,538
In our own lives, the idea that we have to really make that commitment some way.

218
00:23:34,118 --> 00:23:45,231
And that's the whole point really of taking, in the Buddhist tradition, taking refuges and precepts, of actually joining a specific tradition within Buddhism.

219
00:23:45,471 --> 00:23:46,794
It's in all religions.

220
00:23:46,814 --> 00:23:48,736
And that's why it's always ceremonious.

221
00:23:48,836 --> 00:23:51,138
That's why it's always done in community.

222
00:23:51,159 --> 00:23:52,941
It's just like a marriage ceremony.

223
00:23:52,921 --> 00:23:56,365
People I know who've been in partnership for a long time.

224
00:23:56,484 --> 00:23:59,708
I mean, I did a little marriage ceremony for a very old friend of mine.

225
00:24:00,028 --> 00:24:01,950
Partnership for 15 years, you see.

226
00:24:02,431 --> 00:24:05,113
But then a marriage ceremony was something else.

227
00:24:06,894 --> 00:24:08,737
It deepens the commitment to the person.

228
00:24:09,637 --> 00:24:19,428
It's a funny thing, but anybody who's been in a long relationship who goes to a marriage ceremony, and I'm not talking about a religious thing, it's a communal declaration.

229
00:24:19,847 --> 00:24:22,371
Much the way, say, the Quakers do it.

230
00:24:22,654 --> 00:24:23,717
And it has an effect.

231
00:24:23,778 --> 00:24:30,132
It has an effect of deepening that commitment to the other person as person, as an individual.

232
00:24:30,834 --> 00:24:39,954
So you'll find that in all traditions there is that ceremony of being of commitment by the person.

233
00:24:39,934 --> 00:24:45,920
And when I myself became a Buddhist, I did it up at Throstle Hall, and it's five days.

234
00:24:46,441 --> 00:24:49,262
So it's not just a matter of saying a few words.

235
00:24:49,343 --> 00:24:51,726
It was a five-day long...

236
00:24:51,746 --> 00:24:53,166
There were five different ceremonies.

237
00:24:54,087 --> 00:24:58,392
And it was all about this business of renouncing, of burning one's karma.

238
00:24:59,532 --> 00:25:04,497
I can't remember the full gist of it now, but by the end of it, you definitely felt you'd joined something.

239
00:25:06,318 --> 00:25:08,039
And there was that feeling of settlement.

240
00:25:08,059 --> 00:25:09,942
There was that feeling of coming home.

241
00:25:09,922 --> 00:25:16,890
You know, that's one of the big feelings in the spiritual life, that finally you've found your tradition, you've found your teacher.

242
00:25:17,810 --> 00:25:21,095
And it might, I mean, as you know, I didn't stay in the same tradition, I started with Zen.

243
00:25:21,555 --> 00:25:29,864
It's not as though it's blocked in time, that you can't move, but there's that feeling of grounding yourself finally in a spiritual practice.

244
00:25:29,884 --> 00:25:34,950
So that's this crossing of the Rubicon, that's this crossing of the river, you see, and letting go.

245
00:25:36,989 --> 00:25:52,028
So then he joins the great meditation traditions of the time and he goes through two teachers and what these teachers teach him is how to establish ecstasy within himself.

246
00:25:52,008 --> 00:25:55,394
And that means that you don't actually need the world.

247
00:25:55,874 --> 00:26:16,327
Just through the practices of Samatha meditation, concentration meditation, the practices of mantra, the practices of what we call looking at casinas, images, which you then internalize, one begins to recognize that you can actually attain enormous ecstasy within your own heart

248
00:26:16,307 --> 00:26:18,751
without any help from the outside world at all.

249
00:26:19,613 --> 00:26:24,582
So you don't need sex, drugs, rock and roll, you don't need cinema, you don't need anything.

250
00:26:24,602 --> 00:26:34,357
You can actually sit there and develop this enormous state within yourself because that's the capability of the mind and heart within itself.

251
00:26:34,377 --> 00:26:39,987
And once you've established it on an object and you've internalized it, you don't even need that object.

252
00:26:40,709 --> 00:26:44,615
So one of the main places is using the breath.

253
00:26:45,236 --> 00:26:47,118
So you just need the body as it were.

254
00:26:47,439 --> 00:26:59,798
So all you need is, in India anyway, all you need is a bit of shelter, a tree, a bit of clothes, somebody to give you a bit of rice every day, and you sit in ecstasy.

255
00:27:00,807 --> 00:27:13,263
and that's it so you can imagine why it was attractive this is one of the attractions of the monastic life for those who can practice it it's not within everybody's gift

256
00:27:14,846 --> 00:27:16,910
So what does that teach us?

257
00:27:16,970 --> 00:27:22,097
That teaches us that there is another way of actually producing happiness.

258
00:27:22,198 --> 00:27:31,932
But every time he came out of these states, he found himself back in dear old Gautama, back in dear old Siddhartha, just lumped with all this suffering.

259
00:27:32,153 --> 00:27:34,576
It wasn't an answer to sickness, old age and death.

260
00:27:35,017 --> 00:27:37,359
It wasn't an answer to his existential crisis.

261
00:27:37,760 --> 00:27:42,508
It was just another way of displacing his life into a cloud of beauty.

262
00:27:42,488 --> 00:27:43,497
A pink cloud.

263
00:27:43,557 --> 00:27:47,570
It was lovely when he was there, but when he came out, it was pretty audible.

264
00:27:48,192 --> 00:27:51,015
And of course you can get addicted to that like any drug.

265
00:27:52,517 --> 00:27:59,965
So as soon as he began to realize this, of course he recognized that that wasn't the path.

266
00:28:00,266 --> 00:28:05,932
And each time it is said he was so brilliant at his meditation that the teacher would ask him to be a teacher with him.

267
00:28:06,373 --> 00:28:11,618
And each time he said, you know, well, I can't, I don't, I'm not fully satisfied.

268
00:28:11,638 --> 00:28:13,221
There must be something else.

269
00:28:14,180 --> 00:28:28,220
So that's the first thing, that when in your meditation beautiful states arise, fine, you know, we're not trying to get rid of them, we're not trying to destroy beauty or happiness, but that's not the end of the path, that's not what it's about.

270
00:28:28,480 --> 00:28:33,166
So it arises, fantastic, and then you notice it passing away.

271
00:28:33,146 --> 00:28:50,952
And when you see yourself grasping for it as it's passing away, when you come back to the meditation hall with the intention of re-establishing that state, then know that you've fallen into a relationship of attachment, which you could have caused suffering, which could have caused dissatisfaction.

272
00:28:51,794 --> 00:28:55,500
So then abandoning that, he then went into self-mortification.

273
00:28:56,001 --> 00:29:02,835
Now the psychology of self-mortification rests on the idea that all suffering is bodily based.

274
00:29:03,998 --> 00:29:09,448
Now if you think about that, most of it is, where do you experience suffering if it's not in the body?

275
00:29:11,722 --> 00:29:16,511
The hunger, wanting to eat, wanting to see something.

276
00:29:18,615 --> 00:29:20,420
Just the physical pain of the body.

277
00:29:22,222 --> 00:29:29,596
So self-mortification or those exercises, especially the one that he chose, which was to starve oneself.

278
00:29:29,576 --> 00:29:42,105
really reduces the body to, shall we say, almost a skeletal state where, as it were, suffering is lessened in the body.

279
00:29:42,987 --> 00:29:47,636
Now, for those of you, if you've done a 10, if you've done a, anybody done a 10-day fast,

280
00:29:48,595 --> 00:29:49,376
Right.

281
00:29:49,857 --> 00:29:58,662
So I don't know whether you experienced it, but normally the first three days are horrible because there's this huge, all these horrible things are pouring out of the body.

282
00:29:59,525 --> 00:30:04,156
But then you keep drinking water and then there suddenly comes this place where it's absolutely beautiful.

283
00:30:04,136 --> 00:30:05,298
And it remains like that.

284
00:30:05,479 --> 00:30:07,141
It's just absolutely beautiful.

285
00:30:07,161 --> 00:30:08,242
The body doesn't feel hungry.

286
00:30:08,343 --> 00:30:11,386
Of course, it's easing itself, but it doesn't feel hungry.

287
00:30:11,847 --> 00:30:13,068
And your passions are down.

288
00:30:13,130 --> 00:30:14,632
You don't feel passionate about anything.

289
00:30:15,011 --> 00:30:18,016
Everything is lovely subdued, beautifully subdued.

290
00:30:18,676 --> 00:30:24,204
And, of course, you can go on like that until you get close to death, and I think it begins to hurt.

291
00:30:24,184 --> 00:30:48,116
so the idea is just to eat enough just to keep that idea of the body of not exciting the body because it's all based excitement has its base in the senses so all that happened there of course was that he obviously reached these points of suffering and there came this point where we could say he despaired

292
00:30:49,632 --> 00:30:50,633
You're despaired.

293
00:30:51,213 --> 00:30:56,721
Now, that will come to us, the sense of despair about our practice.

294
00:30:56,862 --> 00:30:58,825
And it comes to us because of expectation.

295
00:30:58,884 --> 00:31:02,009
It comes to us because we think we should be somewhere else than where we are.

296
00:31:02,651 --> 00:31:10,321
So there will come these little moments in our spiritual life where we think, nothing's happening, you know, I'm not getting anywhere, and all this sort of stuff.

297
00:31:10,602 --> 00:31:14,086
And they're little jabs of despair, you see.

298
00:31:14,067 --> 00:31:15,672
So you have to be careful of those.

299
00:31:16,153 --> 00:31:23,976
He himself abandoned that self-mortification business and with it his five disciples left him because he said he'd gone soft.

300
00:31:24,631 --> 00:31:53,659
so anyway he wanders off by himself and he's sitting on the roadside and a woman comes along with a bowl of rice pudding which is a very sacred food in Buddhism so he comes along with this bowl of rice pudding and she sees this monk by the roadside and the myth tells us that she thought that it was a god and she offered this food to a god but I think we can realistically say that what she saw was somebody who was on death's door and looking pretty sad

301
00:31:53,638 --> 00:32:19,461
and she probably was carrying it to some sort of family as a gift and when she had a little chat with him she said look you better have this rice pudding so he eats this rice pudding and of course it lifts it lifts his body it lifts his spirits and he can't let go of the idea that there must be an end to suffering it's there within the kernel of the idea is within him

302
00:32:19,441 --> 00:32:34,664
and he must have been reviewing his life and he must have been reviewing everything he's been through and perhaps he's wandered over the three years that he promised his family and he's thinking he might go back and as he's reviewing he remembers this point in childhood

303
00:32:34,644 --> 00:32:42,894
And he must have been about six, seven, maybe eight, and he's watching his father during the ploughing ceremony, just watching his father.

304
00:32:43,635 --> 00:33:02,239
And for some reason, he remembers the quality of that watching, something which obviously he hadn't been aware of, either through the Jhanic meditations, the absorption meditations, or through all these practices which are to do with self-mortification.

305
00:33:02,219 --> 00:33:12,556
And if you think about it, that's quite reasonable because all those practices are about gaining something, about getting something.

306
00:33:12,576 --> 00:33:14,740
You're doing something for something else.

307
00:33:15,220 --> 00:33:18,705
I'm doing the jhana in order to get over sickness, old age and death.

308
00:33:19,186 --> 00:33:22,031
I'm self-mortificating in order to get over.

309
00:33:22,352 --> 00:33:26,538
So it's always drawing that person out of the present moment.

310
00:33:28,087 --> 00:33:34,378
But here he remembers this point where he's watching his father and he's just in the present moment.

311
00:33:35,161 --> 00:33:42,333
Now, if you think of children, especially around the age of three, four, two, three, four, you see it comes naturally.

312
00:33:42,534 --> 00:33:46,079
You know, they see a bug and you see they just absorb into it.

313
00:33:46,381 --> 00:33:48,645
Now they don't have the language to think about it.

314
00:33:49,208 --> 00:33:52,335
And they just absorb into it just out of a total interest.

315
00:33:52,355 --> 00:33:53,376
They're completely there.

316
00:33:53,857 --> 00:33:59,290
And one of the signs that a child is in that state, and we ourselves in that state, is the jaw drops.

317
00:33:59,832 --> 00:34:02,719
And you get parents like my old man used to tell me to shut my mouth.

318
00:34:02,699 --> 00:34:21,365
so shut your mouth son you know you see kids don't you see and what it is is you see is that when there's no jaw when there's no tongue there's no thought if you're in your meditation you might catch that when a thought comes there's a vibration on the tongue because it's just so intimately connected

319
00:34:21,346 --> 00:34:24,750
So it's just like a child, just an absorb into that.

320
00:34:24,829 --> 00:34:32,880
And then you see, after the absorption, after that business of taking in the image, then there's a stop and the child turns around and says, what is it?

321
00:34:32,900 --> 00:34:35,121
So mum says, it's a slug.

322
00:34:35,523 --> 00:34:39,867
So from that point on, you see, there's a title, there's a name, it's a slug.

323
00:34:39,887 --> 00:34:41,789
So that child will never look at a slug again.

324
00:34:42,992 --> 00:34:49,159
What they will see is the image that they had of a slug imposed upon the slug that they now see.

325
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:53,967
And that's the whole distortion that conceptual thinking does for us.

326
00:34:55,268 --> 00:35:07,670
To get back through all that language and all that conception, back to the original mind, back to that original way of seeing things, is the process of enlightenment.

327
00:35:07,786 --> 00:35:29,034
because once we're back there we're back to that amazing intelligence that we have which is now informed see that's the paradox it's been informed through language we couldn't have got here without language we couldn't have got here without the teaching see but now the intelligence is informed it clarifies itself of all those conceptual thinking and it sees anew

328
00:35:29,014 --> 00:35:30,038
So here's the Buddha.

329
00:35:30,077 --> 00:35:34,652
He remembers that moment and he's so inspired by it.

330
00:35:35,014 --> 00:35:36,679
And also remember he's despaired.

331
00:35:36,838 --> 00:35:40,851
He knows now this is it because he doesn't see anything else.

332
00:35:40,871 --> 00:35:42,135
He's been through all the traditions.

333
00:35:42,175 --> 00:35:43,159
He's done everything.

334
00:35:43,730 --> 00:35:54,766
the world can't offer him anything else so he approaches the tree which we now call the Bodhi tree of course and interestingly enough the leaves are shaped like a heart are they not?

335
00:35:55,206 --> 00:36:10,750
sort of and he sits under this big leafy Bodhi tree by the side of the river and he makes this great determination so we've had the great renunciation so now we have the great determination and the determination is

336
00:36:10,730 --> 00:36:32,045
right I've done everything this is it I'm going to sit here and crack this problem or I will die or I will die that's the commitment and it was interesting because when one of my teachers came to the Bihara in Birmingham and

337
00:36:32,025 --> 00:36:37,273
I'd been, I was already ordained for about four or five years or something.

338
00:36:37,612 --> 00:36:44,541
And he came along and I'd been practicing a little bit in India, I remember, but I was living at the Bihar anyway.

339
00:36:45,182 --> 00:36:52,532
And I'd been to Burma before and I'd got very ill with amoebic dysentery and amoebic hepatitis and all sorts of things.

340
00:36:52,512 --> 00:37:00,521
And he wanted me to join him, you see, and he sent one of the monks to tell me, he said, he said, if Anita wants you to come and join him.

341
00:37:00,882 --> 00:37:04,286
So I said, well, frankly, I said, the last time I was in Burma, I nearly died.

342
00:37:05,809 --> 00:37:08,972
I said, I don't particularly have a, you know, I really don't want to go east again.

343
00:37:09,793 --> 00:37:12,416
So he went back, you see, and he came back with a message.

344
00:37:12,436 --> 00:37:16,882
If you're not prepared to die, forget it.

345
00:37:17,402 --> 00:37:22,750
So obviously he was mirroring back to me the memory of the Buddha, you see.

346
00:37:22,769 --> 00:37:23,550
So there's the Buddha.

347
00:37:23,612 --> 00:37:26,135
He's now made this great determination.

348
00:37:26,355 --> 00:37:31,983
So for us, you know, it's little bits, making that determination, determination.

349
00:37:32,003 --> 00:37:40,534
So every time you sit, you see, one of the big mistakes we make is because it's become habitual, we just take a seat.

350
00:37:40,835 --> 00:37:42,077
We just sit here.

351
00:37:42,056 --> 00:37:43,960
And of course, nothing much happens.

352
00:37:44,581 --> 00:37:48,686
The mind wanders, we just get caught up in it, and we might feel a bit more relaxed.

353
00:37:50,309 --> 00:37:53,655
So every time you sit, you have to re-establish that commitment.

354
00:37:53,914 --> 00:37:55,418
And that's your determination.

355
00:37:55,938 --> 00:37:58,541
It's not a great determination, we don't have to worry too much about death.

356
00:37:59,503 --> 00:38:01,786
It's a great determination here, now.

357
00:38:02,467 --> 00:38:07,996
The great determination to commit ourselves 101% to this moment of meditation.

358
00:38:09,614 --> 00:38:10,635
And that's when you get the fruit.

359
00:38:10,735 --> 00:38:12,538
That's when you get the fruits of your practice.

360
00:38:13,699 --> 00:38:17,563
So, as the story goes, of course, he did become enlightened.

361
00:38:17,764 --> 00:38:18,784
It took him six hours.

362
00:38:20,266 --> 00:38:20,947
There's your standard.

363
00:38:20,987 --> 00:38:24,411
If you can sit six hours, you'll probably make it.

364
00:38:24,992 --> 00:38:27,876
So, he became enlightened at that point, you see.

365
00:38:27,916 --> 00:38:38,489
Now, he then spends the first night, the first three nights, trying to understand what he's seen.

366
00:38:38,469 --> 00:38:43,514
Now, when we chant in the morning, I chant the Wheel of Dependent Origination.

367
00:38:43,914 --> 00:38:45,856
So that's the psychology, that's what he understood.

368
00:38:46,657 --> 00:38:51,862
It tells us about why we suffer, the psychology of suffering.

369
00:38:51,882 --> 00:39:06,974
And I do it three times in the thing to commemorate that moment, because he went forward on it, then he saw how it came back on itself, and then he did it again, forward and back, to make sure that he had fully understood the process.

370
00:39:06,954 --> 00:39:09,141
So that's what that chanting is about.

371
00:39:09,161 --> 00:39:10,264
It commemorates that moment.

372
00:39:10,706 --> 00:39:20,577
And that victory verse is what he was supposed to have told Ananda was what he spontaneously spoke when he became enlightened.

373
00:39:23,762 --> 00:39:35,402
So now, having done that, having now made this, which is a moment of realization, realizing what the whole thing was, what is, you see, the next thought?

374
00:39:35,684 --> 00:39:37,646
What is the next thought that comes to mind?

375
00:39:40,251 --> 00:39:41,112
Who can I teach?

376
00:39:42,956 --> 00:39:46,362
You see, with wisdom, compassion arises naturally.

377
00:39:46,695 --> 00:39:48,878
There was no break within that.

378
00:39:48,898 --> 00:39:52,101
It's not, ah, I've done it, fine, great, you know, get back into bed.

379
00:39:54,802 --> 00:39:56,724
It was like it didn't end there.

380
00:39:56,824 --> 00:39:59,447
There was this immediate movement out of the heart.

381
00:39:59,786 --> 00:40:00,648
Who can I teach?

382
00:40:01,409 --> 00:40:03,411
And of course, there's that little doubt.

383
00:40:03,731 --> 00:40:12,719
And again, it's put mythically as the great Brahma Sahampati comes down and says to him, look, he says, there are some with only a little dust in their eyes.

384
00:40:13,519 --> 00:40:16,382
There are people who will understand this stuff, you see.

385
00:40:16,362 --> 00:40:23,688
So it's with that sort of reflection that when he looks at the world, he thinks, who is going to understand this stuff?

386
00:40:24,378 --> 00:40:28,083
And then when he reflects, well, what about my old teachers?

387
00:40:28,342 --> 00:40:30,445
And then he realizes they're dead, they've gone.

388
00:40:30,726 --> 00:40:31,987
So there's a sadness.

389
00:40:32,007 --> 00:40:35,271
And I saw this lovely statue in Burma the last time I was there.

390
00:40:35,311 --> 00:40:36,393
I'd never seen this before.

391
00:40:36,934 --> 00:40:41,400
And he sat in posture like this, but one heart is pointed to his heart like this.

392
00:40:41,840 --> 00:40:44,003
And I said to them, what's the meaning of that?

393
00:40:44,023 --> 00:40:45,244
I'd never seen that mudra.

394
00:40:45,425 --> 00:40:46,487
It's called a mudra posture.

395
00:40:46,927 --> 00:40:51,532
He says it's the sadness he felt when he realized his teachers had died.

396
00:40:53,791 --> 00:41:04,608
So, having done that, he then thinks about this five disciples, remember, who've called him a scab and a deserter, and sort of turned away from him and gone off.

397
00:41:05,168 --> 00:41:09,356
And he wanders off, and he walks, I think it's well over a hundred miles.

398
00:41:10,056 --> 00:41:15,085
So it's not as though he goes next door and says, hey, listen, I'm enlightened now, so I'll give you the message.

399
00:41:15,525 --> 00:41:17,329
He walks, he goes in search.

400
00:41:17,829 --> 00:41:20,894
The teacher goes out in search, you see.

401
00:41:20,875 --> 00:41:28,954
Often it's put in the tradition that the pupil searches for the teacher, you know, that when the teacher's ready, the pupil arises and the pupil's ready to teach and all that sort of stuff.

402
00:41:28,974 --> 00:41:33,423
Well, of course, we in our search have to search for our teacher.

403
00:41:33,885 --> 00:41:39,237
But, you see, the teacher also has to be ready, has to go out and search.

404
00:41:39,217 --> 00:41:46,411
Although I must say, the Indian tradition tends to be for somebody who feels they're ready to sit under a tree and just wait.

405
00:41:47,954 --> 00:41:49,798
And if somebody does come along, that's the test at it.

406
00:41:50,380 --> 00:41:52,324
They must be drawn into the teaching.

407
00:41:53,025 --> 00:41:55,170
But anyway, he makes this great effort to go out and teach.

408
00:41:55,190 --> 00:41:56,733
So that's our compassion.

409
00:41:57,052 --> 00:41:58,476
So now you see...

410
00:41:58,456 --> 00:42:04,514
Every one of us who've meditated, as soon as you say to somebody you've meditated, they expect you to be somehow different.

411
00:42:05,115 --> 00:42:06,099
They say, well, what's the effect?

412
00:42:06,280 --> 00:42:07,483
What's it done for you?

413
00:42:08,085 --> 00:42:09,951
And as soon as you open your mouth, you're teaching them.

414
00:42:11,297 --> 00:42:23,494
So if you go to people and say, well, I go to the Buddhist meditation, yeah, it's fantastic, and you're slowly getting drunk on it, but it's bitter, then people are going to say, well, that's very interesting.

415
00:42:25,938 --> 00:42:31,045
So as soon as you take up a spiritual path, you take responsibility.

416
00:42:31,025 --> 00:42:48,315
And if you are, I mean again, don't get into big false guilt syndromes, but as soon as you don't behave according to a certain standard that the practice demands of you, then of course you're undermining the process of other people's spirituality because they become cynical.

417
00:42:50,018 --> 00:42:54,467
So you take on, whether you like it or not, you take on a certain responsibility.

418
00:42:56,253 --> 00:42:59,637
So having taken on that responsibility, he searches for his disciples.

419
00:43:00,237 --> 00:43:02,820
And of course, he meets them.

420
00:43:02,840 --> 00:43:08,768
And as it's said, as soon as they saw him coming, they realized something had changed about him.

421
00:43:08,809 --> 00:43:10,751
They weren't going to make a seat for him or anything.

422
00:43:10,891 --> 00:43:14,155
But as soon as they saw him coming, they thought, well, no, there's something strange.

423
00:43:14,175 --> 00:43:17,940
And that's when he gives the first talk about his teaching.

424
00:43:17,920 --> 00:43:20,563
And the whole teaching life begins after that.

425
00:43:20,985 --> 00:43:30,920
And he goes on, as you know, to establish an institution, to establish people around him, and eventually had enormous effect on human civilization.

426
00:43:30,940 --> 00:43:35,248
But interestingly enough, that's not the full end of the story.

427
00:43:36,168 --> 00:43:44,282
Because in the scriptures, it says that Mara, the evil one, actually throws doubt

428
00:43:44,599 --> 00:43:47,467
And he attacks, Mara attacks with all his armies.

429
00:43:48,068 --> 00:43:51,838
And this actually happened just after the Enlightenment.

430
00:43:52,760 --> 00:43:57,773
And the question is, who are you to say that you are enlightened?

431
00:43:57,793 --> 00:44:00,920
Who are you to say that you've finished the path?

432
00:44:00,900 --> 00:44:02,744
How do you know that?

433
00:44:02,784 --> 00:44:09,416
So even when he made this huge realization, there was still the doubt, is this really the end of it?

434
00:44:09,536 --> 00:44:11,539
Is this really the end of suffering?

435
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:15,567
Now that doubt, it will always be with us.

436
00:44:15,746 --> 00:44:20,394
That doubt will always be with us and you have to be very careful not to get caught up in doubt.

437
00:44:20,375 --> 00:44:26,143
So, it's not as though the Buddhist teaching is about believing what he said.

438
00:44:26,304 --> 00:44:26,884
We know that.

439
00:44:26,943 --> 00:44:28,326
It's not a belief system.

440
00:44:29,228 --> 00:44:29,869
It's a teaching.

441
00:44:29,909 --> 00:44:30,969
It's a practical teaching.

442
00:44:31,010 --> 00:44:33,793
We put it into practice and it makes sense, etc., etc.

443
00:44:34,414 --> 00:44:41,184
But the doubt, especially in ourselves, you know, that often comes, everybody else can do it but not me.

444
00:44:41,164 --> 00:44:50,259
That's very careful when doubt comes up to make sure you don't get caught up in that thought and that you actually just stay with that position of not knowing.

445
00:44:50,920 --> 00:44:54,945
And that's very difficult for us because the self loves to be in control.

446
00:44:55,007 --> 00:44:55,628
It loves to know.

447
00:44:56,168 --> 00:44:59,152
We all want to know what we're going to do at the end of this course.

448
00:45:00,014 --> 00:45:03,659
We've all got it worked out what's going to happen when we leave this place.

449
00:45:03,679 --> 00:45:05,282
If you didn't, there'd be this anxiety.

450
00:45:05,302 --> 00:45:06,885
What am I going to do?

451
00:45:07,101 --> 00:45:14,291
So it's that case of really staying with that sense of doubt, it's an ugly feeling, and not to get caught up in it.

452
00:45:15,431 --> 00:45:19,956
So he touched the earth as a witness to his enlightenment.

453
00:45:19,978 --> 00:45:23,521
So you'll often find that statue with his hand touching the earth.

454
00:45:23,541 --> 00:45:32,012
And basically, I suppose it's a sort of call to people to say, you know, well, you try and prove me wrong.

455
00:45:31,992 --> 00:45:37,619
Because in my understanding, in my experience, there is now no more suffering in me.

456
00:45:37,719 --> 00:45:40,021
I don't experience suffering at any level.

457
00:45:40,342 --> 00:45:42,264
That's not physical suffering for those of you.

458
00:45:42,726 --> 00:45:43,766
The body always has pain.

459
00:45:44,307 --> 00:45:45,088
It's the heart.

460
00:45:45,349 --> 00:45:49,393
There's no more of all this depression, anxiety, all the gamut of human misery.

461
00:45:50,014 --> 00:45:52,177
That's all gone.

462
00:45:52,157 --> 00:45:58,128
But, interestingly enough, for seven years Mara hunts him.

463
00:45:59,088 --> 00:46:03,036
So it's an interesting thing in the scripture that we have this figure of Mara.

464
00:46:03,056 --> 00:46:10,527
Now you can either see it, of course, as some sort of devil, but you can see it as traces within the Buddha's mind, still there, little traces.

465
00:46:11,088 --> 00:46:13,793
So there's been this huge enlightenment, but there's still little traces.

466
00:46:14,394 --> 00:46:17,119
And Mara sends his three daughters.

467
00:46:17,099 --> 00:46:19,724
Lust, sensual pleasure, and boredom.

468
00:46:20,085 --> 00:46:22,771
So he obviously had a big problem with lust.

469
00:46:23,251 --> 00:46:27,882
If you compare that with Jesus Christ, interesting, because Christ seems to have been powered, doesn't he?

470
00:46:28,101 --> 00:46:28,943
Took him up to the mountain.

471
00:46:29,644 --> 00:46:32,391
So those are the three, those are your four...

472
00:46:32,371 --> 00:46:59,474
worldly pursuits fame, friendship, riches power and of course seeking pleasure in the sensual world so the Buddha is obviously around well he'd had a good life hadn't he all that pleasure stuff you know and his three daughters kept tempting him now interestingly enough why was boredom there you see because boredom is part of that pleasure syndrome the more pleasure you have

473
00:47:00,063 --> 00:47:01,706
the more it becomes obsolescent.

474
00:47:01,766 --> 00:47:03,809
You've always got to go for a bigger kick.

475
00:47:04,510 --> 00:47:07,797
And therefore, what moves you is the boredom of where you are.

476
00:47:08,157 --> 00:47:10,682
So boredom is the great motivator towards addiction.

477
00:47:12,186 --> 00:47:17,936
So whenever you're bored, bored in your meditation, you never feed the boredom by distraction.

478
00:47:18,170 --> 00:47:21,773
You feed the boredom by, you undermine boredom by repetition.

479
00:47:22,514 --> 00:47:29,360
So when you're sitting there watching the breath and there's just this huge thing, this is so boring, you know.

480
00:47:29,380 --> 00:47:33,726
So you feel the boredom, you know it's there, but you just keep watching the breath.

481
00:47:33,746 --> 00:47:37,429
And then eventually it fades away, you see, because you're not feeding it.

482
00:47:38,050 --> 00:47:38,630
You know it's there.

483
00:47:38,670 --> 00:47:39,931
Remember, you've got to feel these things.

484
00:47:40,371 --> 00:47:41,793
You've got to actually experience them.

485
00:47:41,813 --> 00:47:43,215
You mustn't push them away, huh?

486
00:47:44,900 --> 00:47:51,773
So there comes a point, of course, when, and it's said seven years, which is one of these mythical cycles, isn't it?

487
00:47:51,793 --> 00:47:52,255
Seven years.

488
00:47:53,277 --> 00:47:57,847
His daughters, you know, haven't been successful.

489
00:47:57,887 --> 00:48:00,192
They go to Mara, their dad, and say, look...

490
00:48:00,172 --> 00:48:04,016
Oh no, Mara sees that he hasn't been successful.

491
00:48:04,036 --> 00:48:08,222
He just can't get through to the Buddha to tempt him into all these things again.

492
00:48:08,722 --> 00:48:10,365
And so he says to his daughter, look, let's forget it.

493
00:48:10,726 --> 00:48:11,606
It's not working.

494
00:48:12,148 --> 00:48:14,731
And his daughter says, well, let's have just one more go, Dad.

495
00:48:15,793 --> 00:48:17,434
But eventually he slinks off.

496
00:48:17,835 --> 00:48:18,996
And what does the daughter say?

497
00:48:19,056 --> 00:48:19,918
Why are you going?

498
00:48:20,018 --> 00:48:22,942
Why is it that you are abandoning this quest?

499
00:48:23,583 --> 00:48:27,208
And Mara says, the Buddha sees me.

500
00:48:27,188 --> 00:48:37,507
And it's seeing, it's seeing what all the world has to offer as vanity, as emptiness, that undermines its power over us.

501
00:48:37,869 --> 00:48:49,871
So that by that time, it would seem that all, whatever was there by ancient conditioning was completely drained out over those seven years.

502
00:48:54,711 --> 00:48:56,215
And then finally, what can we expect?

503
00:48:56,456 --> 00:48:59,463
What can we expect from this sort of training, you see?

504
00:48:59,945 --> 00:49:07,905
Well, there's this lovely tale in the scriptures where somebody says to the Buddha, look, this training you're going on about is bloody difficult.

505
00:49:07,925 --> 00:49:08,726
And he said, well, it is.

506
00:49:08,847 --> 00:49:09,409
It's hard.

507
00:49:09,429 --> 00:49:11,032
You've got to commit yourself and all that.

508
00:49:11,012 --> 00:49:13,295
And he said, okay, so what?

509
00:49:13,356 --> 00:49:16,498
He said, what do you get to Nibbana?

510
00:49:16,518 --> 00:49:17,960
Nibbana says, so what?

511
00:49:18,320 --> 00:49:21,143
What do you get when you get to Nibbana?

512
00:49:21,164 --> 00:49:25,148
He says, when you achieve Nibbana, you are happy and with it contented.

513
00:49:25,688 --> 00:49:26,570
And he's talking about himself.

514
00:49:26,929 --> 00:49:29,572
You are joyful and with it contented.

515
00:49:30,454 --> 00:49:40,664
And when it comes to his own time to die, there's a lovely scripture where basically he just waits for the body to die.

516
00:49:40,882 --> 00:49:43,829
And he's just lying there on his side, and the people have come around him.

517
00:49:44,311 --> 00:49:48,402
Even at the end, he's ready to take somebody into the order, isn't he?

518
00:49:48,722 --> 00:49:53,074
Right at the end, right before he dies, he's ready to accept somebody in the order.

519
00:49:53,094 --> 00:49:55,902
And there he is, he's dying, and most of us are freaked out, eh?

520
00:49:55,882 --> 00:49:57,626
Most of us don't want anybody around.

521
00:49:57,706 --> 00:50:04,155
But here's this lovely peace and just this letting go of the body.

522
00:50:04,175 --> 00:50:04,876
Letting go of the body.

523
00:50:05,436 --> 00:50:07,721
And of course, great sadness from that, from the younger monks.

524
00:50:07,740 --> 00:50:09,884
They all start crying, you see, and the nuns and all that.

525
00:50:10,324 --> 00:50:11,626
And the elders say, what do you expect?

526
00:50:12,208 --> 00:50:13,769
Everything arises and passes away.

527
00:50:15,452 --> 00:50:16,934
And that was one of the Buddha's pet sayings.

528
00:50:17,715 --> 00:50:19,117
Everything arises and passes away.

529
00:50:19,177 --> 00:50:22,362
There's nothing in this world worth holding on to.

530
00:50:22,342 --> 00:50:31,322
Nothing in this world worth holding on to.

531
00:50:31,342 --> 00:50:38,079
So, I hope that's been of some use to you in terms of how to reflect upon your own spiritual life.

532
00:50:38,880 --> 00:50:42,208
And that's it.
